# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: crm-systems
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:crm-systems/contact-manager] A **contact manager** is a software program that enables users to easily store and find contact information, such as names, addresses and telephone numbers.
[src:crm-systems/contact-manager] They are databases that provide an integrated approach to tracking information and communication activities linked to contacts.
[src:crm-systems/contact-manager] Simple ones for personal use are included in most smartphones.
[src:crm-systems/contact-manager] Sophisticated contact managers provide calendar sharing features and allow colleagues to access the same database.
[src:crm-systems/contact-manager] Contact lists have been available for a long time.
[src:crm-systems/contact-manager] An early contact management system was Exsell for DOS by Excalibur Sources, released in 1984.
[src:crm-systems/contact-manager] Microsoft Windows has included different contact managers over time: Cardfile, Windows Address Book, Windows Contacts, People and Outlook for Windows.
[src:crm-systems/contact-manager] Traditionally, a contact manager is usually used for instances where the sales interaction model of the organization is a one-to-many interaction model, in which a single sales representative is responsible for multiple roles within a company.
[src:crm-systems/contact-manager] Alternatively, a company with a many-to-many interaction model, in which many sales representatives are targeting a single job role, a customer relationship management system is preferred.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] CRM systems compile data from a range of different communication channels, including a company's website, telephone (which many services come with a softphone), email, live chat, marketing materials, and more recently, social media.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] They allow businesses to learn more about their target audiences and how to better cater to their needs, thus retaining customers and driving sales growth.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] CRM may be used with past, present or potential customers.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] The concepts, procedures, and rules that a corporation follows when communicating with its consumers are referred to as CRM.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] This complete connection covers direct contact with customers, such as sales and service-related operations, forecasting, and the analysis of consumer patterns and behaviours, from the perspective of the company.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] The concept of customer relationship management started in the early 1970s, when customer satisfaction was evaluated using annual surveys or by front-line asking.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] At that time, businesses had to rely on standalone mainframe systems to automate sales, but the extent of technology allowed them to categorize customers in spreadsheets and lists.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] One of the best-known precursors of modern-day CRM is the Farley File.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Developed by Franklin Roosevelt's campaign manager, James Farley, the Farley File was a comprehensive set of records detailing political and personal facts about people FDR and Farley met or were supposed to meet.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Using it, people that FDR met were impressed by his "recall" of facts about their family and what they were doing professionally and politically.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Kestenbaum introduced the concept of database marketing, namely applying statistical methods to analyze and gather customer data.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] By 1987, Pat Sullivan and Mike Muhney had released a customer evaluation system called ACT! based on the principle of a digital Rolodex, which offered a contact management service for the first time.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] The trend was followed by numerous companies and independent developers trying to maximize lead potential, including Tom Siebel of Siebel Systems, who designed the first CRM product, Siebel Customer Relationship Management, in 1993.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] This included embedding sales force automation or extended customer service (e.g. inquiry, activity management) as CRM features in their ERP.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Customer relationship management was popularized in 1997 due to the work of Siebel, Gartner, and IBM.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Between 1997 and 2000, leading CRM products were enriched with shipping and marketing capabilities.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Siebel introduced the first mobile CRM app called Siebel Sales Handheld in 1999.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] The idea of a stand-alone, cloud-hosted customer base was soon adopted by other leading providers at the time, including PeopleSoft (acquired by Oracle), Oracle, SAP and Salesforce.com.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] The first open-source CRM system was developed by SugarCRM in 2004.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] During this period, CRM was rapidly migrating to the cloud, as a result of which it became accessible to sole entrepreneurs and small teams.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] This increase in accessibility generated a huge wave of price reduction.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Around 2009, developers began considering the options to profit from social media's momentum and designed tools to help companies become accessible on all users' favourite networks.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Many startups at the time benefited from this trend to provide exclusively social CRM solutions, including Base and Nutshell.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] The same year, Gartner organized and held the first Customer Relationship Management Summit, and summarized the features systems should offer to be classified as CRM solutions.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] In 2013 and 2014, most of the popular CRM products were linked to business intelligence systems and communication software to improve corporate communication and end-users' experience.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] The leading trend is to replace standardized CRM solutions with industry-specific ones, or to make them customizable enough to meet the needs of every business.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] In November 2016, Forrester released a report where it "identified the nine most significant CRM suites from eight prominent vendors".
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Strategic CRM concentrates upon the development of a customer-centric business culture.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] The focus of a business on being customer-centric (in design and implementation of their CRM strategy) will translate into an improved CLV.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] The primary goal of CRM systems is integration and automation of sales, marketing, and customer support.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Therefore, these systems typically have a dashboard that gives an overall view of the three functions on a single customer view, a single page for each customer that a company may have.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] The dashboard may provide client information, past sales, previous marketing efforts, and more, summarizing all of the relationships between the customer and the firm.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Operational CRM is made up of three main components: sales force automation, marketing automation, and service automation.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] The role of analytical CRM systems is to analyze customer data collected through multiple sources and present it so that business managers can make more informed decisions.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Analytical CRM systems use techniques such as data mining, correlation, and pattern recognition to analyze customer data.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] These analytics help improve customer service by finding small problems which can be solved, perhaps by marketing to different parts of a consumer audience differently.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] For example, through the analysis of a customer base's buying behavior, a company might see that this customer base has not been buying a lot of products recently.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] After reviewing their data, the company might think to market to this subset of consumers differently to best communicate how this company's products might benefit this group specifically.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] The third primary aim of CRM systems is to incorporate external stakeholders such as suppliers, vendors, and distributors, and to share customer information across groups, departments, and organizations.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] For example, feedback can be collected from technical support calls, which could help provide direction for marketing products and services to that particular customer in the future.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] A customer data platform (CDP) is a computer system used by marketing departments that assembles data about individual people from various sources into one database, with which other software systems can interact.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] As of February 2017, about twenty companies were selling such systems and revenue for them was around US$300 million.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] When building and managing customer relationships through marketing, firms might benefit from using a variety of tools to help organizational design, incentive schemes, customer structures, and more to optimize the reach of their marketing campaigns.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Through the acknowledgment of the distinct phases of CRM, businesses will be able to benefit from seeing the interaction of multiple relationships as connected transactions.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] The final factor of CRM highlights the importance of CRM through accounting for the profitability of customer relationships.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] By studying the particular spending habits of customers, a firm may be able to dedicate different resources and amounts of attention to different types of consumers.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] CRM systems may also incorporate automation features to streamline repetitive tasks such as data entry, follow-ups, and customer segmentation.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Relational Intelligence, which is the awareness of the variety of relationships a customer can have with a firm and the ability of the firm to reinforce or change those connections, is an important component of the main phases of CRM.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Companies may be good at capturing demographic data, such as gender, age, income, and education, and connecting them with purchasing information to categorize customers into profitability tiers, but this is only a firm's industrial view of customer relationships.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] A lack of relational intelligence is a sign that firms still see customers as resources that can be used for up-sell or cross-sell opportunities, rather than people looking for interesting and personalized interactions.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Customer satisfaction has important implications for the economic performance of firms because it has the ability to increase customer loyalty and usage behavior and reduce customer complaints and the likelihood of customer defection.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] The implementation of a CRM approach is likely to affect customer satisfaction and customer knowledge for a variety of different reasons.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Firstly, firms can customize their offerings for each customer.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] By accumulating information across customer interactions and processing this information to discover hidden patterns, CRM applications help firms customize their offerings to suit the individual tastes of their customers.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] This customization enhances the perceived quality of products and services from a customer's viewpoint, and because the perceived quality is a determinant of customer satisfaction, it follows that CRM applications indirectly affect customer satisfaction.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] CRM applications also enable firms to provide timely, accurate processing of customer orders and requests and the ongoing management of customer accounts.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] For example, Piccoli and Applegate discuss how Wyndham uses IT tools to deliver a consistent service experience across its various properties to a customer.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Both an improved ability to customize and reduced variability of the consumption experience enhance perceived quality, which in turn positively affects customer satisfaction.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] CRM applications also help firms manage customer relationships more effectively across the stages of relationship initiation, maintenance, and termination.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] With CRM systems, customers are served on the day-to-day process.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] With more reliable information, their demand for self-service from companies will decrease.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] If there is less need to interact with the company for different problems, then the customer satisfaction level is expected to increase.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] These central benefits of CRM will be connected hypothetically to the three kinds of equity, which are relationship, value, and brand, and in the end to customer equity.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Eight benefits were recognized to provide value drivers.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Enhanced sales force efficiency and effectiveness.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Improved customer service efficiency and effectiveness.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Individualized marketing messages are also called campaigns.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Connect customers and all channels on a single platform.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Research has found a 5% increase in customer retention boosts lifetime customer profits by 50% on average across multiple industries, as well as a boost of up to 90% within specific industries such as insurance.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Companies that have mastered customer relationship strategies have the most successful CRM programs.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] For example, MBNA Europe has had a 75% annual profit growth since 1995.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] The firm heavily invests in screening potential cardholders.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Once proper clients are identified, the firm retains 97% of its profitable customers.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] They implement CRM by marketing the right products to the right customers.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] The firm's customers' card usage is 52% above the industry norm, and the average expenditure is 30% more per transaction.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Also 10% of their account holders ask for more information on cross-sale products.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Amazon has also seen successes through its customer proposition.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] The firm implemented personal greetings, collaborative filtering, and more for the customer.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] They also used CRM training for the employees to see up to 80% of customers repeat.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] A customer profile is a detailed description of any particular classification of customer which is created to represent the typical users of a product or service.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Customer profiling is a method to understand your customers in terms of demographics, behaviour and lifestyle.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] It is used to help make customer-focused decisions without confusing the scope of the project with personal opinion.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Overall profiling is gathering information that sums up consumption habits so far and projects them into the future so that they can be grouped for marketing and advertising purposes.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Customer or consumer profiles are the essences of the data that is collected alongside core data (name, address, company) and processed through customer analytics methods, essentially a type of profiling.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] The three basic methods of customer profiling are the psychographic approach, the consumer typology approach, and the consumer characteristics approach.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] These customer profiling methods help you design your business around who your customers are and help you make better customer-centered decisions.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Consultants hold that it is important for companies to establish strong CRM systems to improve their relational intelligence.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] According to this argument, a company must recognize that people have many different types of relationships with different brands.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] One research study analyzed relationships between consumers in China, Germany, Spain, and the United States, with over 200 brands in 11 industries including airlines, cars, and media.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] This information is valuable as it provides demographic, behavioral, and value-based customer segmentation.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] These types of relationships can be both positive and negative.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Some customers view themselves as friends of the brands, while others as enemies, and some are mixed with a love-hate relationship with the brand.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Some relationships are distant, intimate, or anything in between.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Managers must understand the different reasons for the types of relationships, and provide the customer with what they are looking for.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Companies can collect this information by using surveys, interviews, and more, with current customers.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Companies must also improve the relational intelligence of their CRM systems.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Companies store and receive huge amounts of data through emails, online chat sessions, phone calls, and more.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Many companies do not properly make use of this great amount of data, however.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] All of these are signs of what types of relationships the customer wants with the firm, and therefore companies may consider investing more time and effort in building out their relational intelligence.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Companies can use data mining technologies and web searches to understand relational signals.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Social media such as social networking sites, blogs, and forums can also be used to collect and analyze information.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Understanding the customer and capturing this data allows companies to convert customers' signals into information and knowledge that the firm can use to understand a potential customer's desired relations with a brand.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Many firms have also implemented training programs to teach employees how to recognize and create strong customer-brand relationships.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Other employees have also been trained in social psychology and the social sciences to help bolster customer relationships.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Customer service representatives must be trained to value customer relationships and trained to understand existing customer profiles.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Even the finance and legal departments should understand how to manage and build relationships with customers.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Contact centre CRM providers are popular for small and mid-market businesses.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] These systems codify the interactions between the company and customers by using analytics and key performance indicators to give the users information on where to focus their marketing and customer service.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] This allows agents to have access to a caller's history to provide personalized customer communication.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] The intention is to maximize average revenue per user, decrease churn rate and decrease idle and unproductive contact with the customers.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Growing in popularity is the idea of gamifying, or using game design elements and principles in a non-game environment, such as customer service settings.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] The gamification of customer service environments includes providing elements found in games, like rewards and bonus points, to customer service representatives as a method of feedback for a job well done.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Gamification tools can motivate agents by tapping into their desire for rewards, recognition, achievements, and competition.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Contact-center automation, CCA, the practice of having an integrated system that coordinates contacts between an organization and the public, is designed to reduce the repetitive and tedious parts of a contact center agent's job.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Automation prevents this by having pre-recorded audio messages that help customers solve their problems.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] For example, an automated contact center may be able to re-route a customer through a series of commands asking him or her to select a certain number to speak with a particular contact center agent who specializes in the field in which the customer has a question.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Software tools can also integrate with the agent's desktop tools to handle customer questions and requests.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] This also saves time on behalf of the employees.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Social CRM involves the use of social media and technology to engage and learn from consumers.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Because the public, especially young people, are increasingly using social networking sites, companies use these sites to draw attention to their products, services and brands, with the aim of building up customer relationships to increase demand.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] With the increase in the use of social media platforms, integrating CRM with the help of social media can potentially be a quicker and more cost-friendly process.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Some CRM systems integrate social media sites like Twitter, LinkedIn, and Facebook to track and communicate with customers.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] These customers also share their own opinions and experiences with a company's products and services, giving these firms more insight.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Therefore, these firms can both share their own views and track the opinions of their customers.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Enterprise feedback management software platforms combine internal survey data with trends identified through social media to allow businesses to make more accurate decisions on which products to supply.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] CRM systems can also include technologies that create geographic marketing campaigns.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] The systems take in information based on a customer's physical location and sometimes integrates it with popular location-based GPS applications.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] It can be used for networking or contact management as well to help increase sales based on location.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Despite the general notion that CRM systems were created for customer-centric businesses, they can also be applied to B2B environments to streamline and improve customer management conditions.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] For the best level of CRM operation in a B2B environment, the software must be personalized and delivered at individual levels.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] The main differences between business-to-consumer (B2C) and business-to-business CRM systems concern aspects like sizing of contact databases and length of relationships.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] In the Gartner CRM Summit 2010 challenges like "system tries to capture data from social networking traffic like Twitter, handles Facebook page addresses or other online social networking sites" were discussed and solutions were provided that would help in bringing more clientele.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] The era of the "social customer" refers to the use of social media by customers.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Some CRM systems are equipped with mobile capabilities, making information accessible to remote sales staff.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Many CRM vendors offer subscription-based web tools (cloud computing) and SaaS.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Salesforce.com was the first company to provide enterprise applications through a web browser, and has maintained its leadership position.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Over the years, the number of SaaS providers has grown with CRM being the leading category for 2024.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Traditional providers moved into the cloud-based market via acquisitions of smaller providers: Oracle purchased RightNow in October 2011, and Taleo and Eloqua in 2012; SAP acquired SuccessFactors in December 2011 and NetSuite acquired Verenia in 2022.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Sales forces also play an important role in CRM, as maximizing sales effectiveness and increasing sales productivity is a driving force behind the adoption of CRM software.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Some of the top CRM trends identified in 2021 include focusing on customer service automation such as chatbots, hyper-personalization based on customer data and insights, and the use of unified CRM systems.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] CRM vendors support sales productivity with different products, such as tools that measure the effectiveness of ads that appear in 3D video games.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Pharmaceutical companies were some of the first investors in sales force automation (SFA) and some are on their third- or fourth-generation implementations.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] However, until recently, the deployments did not extend beyond SFA—limiting their scope and interest to Gartner analysts.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Another related development is vendor relationship management (VRM), which provide tools and services that allow customers to manage their individual relationship with vendors.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] VRM development has grown out of efforts by ProjectVRM at Harvard's Berkman Center for Internet & Society and Identity Commons' Internet Identity Workshops, as well as by a growing number of startups and established companies.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] VRM was the subject of a cover story in the May 2010 issue of *CRM* Magazine.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Another trend worth noting is the rise of Customer Success as a discipline within companies.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] More and more companies establish Customer Success teams as separate from the traditional Sales team and task them with managing existing customer relations.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] This trend fuels demand for additional capabilities for a more holistic understanding of customer health, which is a limitation for many existing vendors in the space.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] As a result, a growing number of new entrants enter the market while existing vendors add capabilities in this area to their suites.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] In 2017, artificial intelligence and predictive analytics were identified as the newest trends in CRM.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Companies face large challenges when trying to implement CRM systems.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Consumer companies frequently manage their customer relationships haphazardly and unprofitably.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] They may not effectively or adequately use their connections with their customers, due to misunderstandings or misinterpretations of a CRM system's analysis.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Clients may be treated like an exchange party, rather than a unique individual, due to, occasionally, a lack of a bridge between the CRM data and the CRM analysis output.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Many studies show that customers are frequently frustrated by a company's inability to meet their relationship expectations, and on the other side, companies do not always know how to translate the data they have gained from CRM software into a feasible action plan.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] In 2003, a Gartner report estimated that more than $2 billion had been spent on software that was not being used.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] According to CSO Insights, less than 40 percent of 1,275 participating companies had end-user adoption rates above 90 percent.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Many corporations only use CRM systems on a partial or fragmented basis.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] In a 2007 survey from the UK, four-fifths of senior executives reported that their biggest challenge is getting their staff to use the systems they had installed.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Forty-three percent of respondents said they use less than half the functionality of their existing systems.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] However, market research regarding consumers' preferences may increase the adoption of CRM among developing countries' consumers.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Collection of customer data such as personally identifiable information must strictly obey customer privacy laws, which often requires extra expenditures on legal support.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Part of the paradox with CRM stems from the challenge of determining exactly what CRM is and what it can do for a company.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] The CRM paradox, also referred to as the "dark side of CRM", may entail favoritism and differential treatment of some customers.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] This can happen because a business prioritizes customers who are more profitable, more relationship-orientated or tend to have increased loyalty to the company.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Although focusing on such customers by itself is not a bad thing, it can leave other customers feeling left out and alienated, potentially decreasing profits.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] CRM technologies can easily become ineffective if there is no proper management, and they are not implemented correctly.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] The data sets must also be connected, distributed, and organized properly so that the users can access the information that they need quickly and easily.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Research studies also show that customers are increasingly becoming dissatisfied with contact center experiences due to lags and wait times.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] They also request and demand multiple channels of communication with a company, and these channels must transfer information seamlessly.
[src:crm-systems/customer-relationship-management] Therefore, it is increasingly important for companies to deliver a cross-channel customer experience that can be both consistent as well as reliable.
[src:crm-systems/lead-management] The general principles of lead management create an ordered structure for managing volumes of business inquiries, frequently termed leads.
[src:crm-systems/lead-management] The process creates an architecture for organization of data, distributed across the various stages of a sales process, and across a distributed sales force.
[src:crm-systems/lead-management] While simple in scope, lead (or inquiry) flow process can become complex as clients, prospective clients, and sales professionals interact.
[src:crm-systems/lead-management] Interactions and subsequent actions create a variety of potential outcomes, both productive and counter-productive to business development.
[src:crm-systems/lead-management] This ever-increasing number of scenarios creates functional disconnects, in other words, critical opportunities to mishandle an inquiry that reduces or destroys its potential value.
[src:crm-systems/lead-management] Appropriate management of these scenarios is the function of lead management and is the basis of software such as marketing automation.
[src:crm-systems/lead-management] Generating a lead, or lead generation can relate to myriad marketing technologies and methodologies.
[src:crm-systems/lead-management] Regardless of how it is achieved, however, from an architectural perspective lead generation is simply the ability to attract the interest of a consumer and capture enough data to validate and prioritize their interest, then contact them.
[src:crm-systems/lead-management] Lead acquisition is the first, and possibly the most critical potential disconnect in the lead management process.
[src:crm-systems/lead-management] With billions being spent on advertising expenditures, in many cases the value of those expenditures is reduced because relevant information from responses is not collected or distributed.
[src:crm-systems/lead-management] The value of this process is tightly linked to a variety of consumer response theories that highlight the relevance and responsiveness of the customer experience as being key ingredients in turning potential customers into actual customers.
[src:crm-systems/lead-management] Once acquired, the speed, accuracy, and relevance of response can greatly influence a potential consumer's decision to buy, or not buy, a product or service.
[src:crm-systems/lead-management] One relevant example of this process is the use of the Internet, online marketing, and Web analytics for high-level lead generation.
[src:crm-systems/lead-management] A consumer generally uses the Internet and makes Internet inquiries for products and services out of a desire for convenience and efficiency of their time.
[src:crm-systems/lead-management] Consequently, they expect a timely, relevant response to inquiries made.
[src:crm-systems/lead-management] If the acquisition and distribution of data collected during their inquiry is not effective, the consumer experience will be negative.
[src:crm-systems/lead-management] No response, poor response, too-early or too late response equals negative impact on consumer attitudes and behavior.
[src:crm-systems/lead-management] For this particular medium, the lead acquisition architecture generally consists of a Web form to collect consumer data, a database to temporarily or persistently store that information for subsequent distribution, and a software application to distribute the data at appropriate levels.
[src:crm-systems/lead-management] The distribution architecture will vary widely depending upon the objective of the lead generation.
[src:crm-systems/lead-management] Generation for the purpose of selling the inquiry itself to another organization would typically include a methodology for selecting one or more buyers and then transmitting the lead via a variety of potential means, like: XML, name–value pairs, fax, email, telephone.
[src:crm-systems/lead-management] In the case of leads generated for an organization's own use it may simply consist of a web page to render the contents of the lead database or a simple email action from the Web form itself.
[src:crm-systems/lead-management] Once the lead information is collected and distributed, it is then transferred to a marketing and/or sales management department, who will continue to implement lead management practices in pursuit of completion of a sale.
[src:crm-systems/lead-management] Established lead management practices should provide the needed connectivity and accountability between those two operational units, and when managed properly, enhances the effectiveness of both operations.
[src:crm-systems/lead-management] The architectural relationship is much akin to the order carousel in a short order diner.
[src:crm-systems/lead-management] This carousel is the communication and accountability between the waiter and the cook.
[src:crm-systems/lead-management] Without this simple coordination orders would be lost, prepared incorrectly, or prepared in random order missing the expectations of the customer.
[src:crm-systems/lead-management] For management teams with a solid foundation in lead management principles, the process should create increased efficiency and accountability between marketing and sales activities.
[src:crm-systems/lead-management] For marketing, this portion of the architecture primarily manages the analytics of the lead generation, distribution, and disposition.
[src:crm-systems/lead-management] For sales, the architecture provides a fast, accurate method of distribution, in addition to improved management and accountability processes for sales activity.
[src:crm-systems/lead-management] The central hub of the lead management process once the prior architectures are in place is communication.
[src:crm-systems/lead-management] Effective lead management principles requires intensive and accurate high-level communication, both internally within organizations, and externally to the lead inquiries.
[src:crm-systems/lead-management] Communications functions should include intelligent sourcing of inquiry information, and provide appropriate vehicles for overt contacting methods such as phone, email, or other communication forms.
[src:crm-systems/lead-management] In many cases, especially where inquiries may not be ready to work with businesses immediately, it is crucial to maintain ongoing nurturing communications that cultivate a lead into future sales, and effective lead management practices include these methods.
[src:crm-systems/lead-management] The analytics architecture is the last, and once the other architectures are in place, the most critical piece of an effective lead management system.
[src:crm-systems/lead-management] This portion of the architecture allows for the dynamic review and analysis of lead actions, marketing channels, and sales performance.
[src:crm-systems/lead-management] Software of this type is called marketing attribution.
[src:crm-systems/lead-management] For many organizations, being a pipeline marketing organization that optimizes for post lead metrics such as revenue can be vital in decision making that improve production, return on investment, and the overall performance and cost benefits of their marketing and sales strategies.
[src:crm-systems/lead-management] As larger vendors work with partner organizations such as distributors, resellers, brokers and other channel partners, those vendors often distribute leads to their respective partners to provide a local contact to those prospects and also 'feed' partners with new business opportunities.
[src:crm-systems/lead-management] Today there are two major methods for distributing sales leads to partners: Push or Pull.
[src:crm-systems/lead-management] The **lead acquisition** functionality should allow for the simple and efficient acquisition of lead data into the lead management system.
[src:crm-systems/lead-management] The acquisition functions must be able to support a variety of marketing channels and methods of capturing data.
[src:crm-systems/lead-management] This acquisition function may include the transfer of discrete lead data via technologies like name–value pairs, XML, RSS, HTTP POST, and FTP.
[src:crm-systems/lead-management] These technologies can be used in conjunction with an organization's own website or third party lead provider.
[src:crm-systems/lead-management] Often lead providers will deliver leads via a standard email.
[src:crm-systems/lead-management] These leads can be electronically captured by parsing the email and then submitting the lead using one of the methods described above.
[src:crm-systems/lead-management] This acquisition function may include imports of multiple leads' data via technologies like Microsoft Excel, CSV, or other formatted batch data values.
[src:crm-systems/lead-management] These technologies can be used to acquire leads that have been stored in other systems, assembled from lists, or other volume sources.
[src:crm-systems/lead-management] This acquisition function may include Web landing pages or sales interfaces.
[src:crm-systems/lead-management] This technology can be used to acquire discrete lead data via manual input into an application-type form.
[src:crm-systems/lead-management] Businesses need to keep track of all inquiries and sales leads that are generated from numerous sources and know the conversion from the source of various sales leads.
[src:crm-systems/lead-management] A good inquiry management system can save time.
[src:crm-systems/lead-management] Most lead management systems can filtering and categorizing lead data.
[src:crm-systems/lead-management] There are myriad ways to accomplish this process and some of them may be specific to industries.
[src:crm-systems/marketing-automation] Marketing automation tracks top-of-funnel activities to drive prospects to sales.
[src:crm-systems/marketing-automation] This is contrasted with CRM, which manages information about the prospect and their position in the sales cycle.
[src:crm-systems/marketing-automation] The use of marketing automation makes processes that would otherwise be performed manually much more efficient and enables new processes.
[src:crm-systems/marketing-automation] Marketing automation can be defined as the use of technology to automate several repetitive tasks that are carried out regularly as part of a marketing campaign.
[src:crm-systems/marketing-automation] Marketing Automation platforms allow marketers to automate and simplify client communication by managing complex omnichannel marketing strategies with a single tool.
[src:crm-systems/marketing-automation] Marketing Automation assists in areas such as lead generation, segmentation, lead nurturing and lead scoring, relationship marketing, Cross-sell and upsell, Retention, and Marketing ROI measurement.
[src:crm-systems/marketing-automation] Effective marketing automation tools leverage data from a separate or integrated CRM to understand customer impact and preferences.
[src:crm-systems/marketing-automation] Marketing automation platforms are also used to schedule campaigns and monitor customer engagement across multiple digital channels.
[src:crm-systems/marketing-automation] Uses tracking codes in social media, email, and webpages to track the behavior of anyone interested in a product or service to gain a measure of intent.
[src:crm-systems/marketing-automation] It can record which social media group or thread they followed, which link was clicked on in an email or which search term was used to access a website.
[src:crm-systems/marketing-automation] Multiple link analysis can then track buyer behavior - following links and multiple threads related to product A, but not B will show an interest only in A.
[src:crm-systems/marketing-automation] This allows more accurately targeted response and the development of a nurturing program specifically targeted towards their interest and vertical market.
[src:crm-systems/marketing-automation] This allows businesses to more efficiently and effectively reach target consumers who show, through their internet history behavior, that they will be interested in the company's products.
[src:crm-systems/marketing-automation] Due to its interactive nature, this has been described as Marketing Automation 2.0.
[src:crm-systems/marketing-automation] Has a focus on moving leads from the top of the marketing funnel through to becoming sales-ready leads at the bottom of the funnel.
[src:crm-systems/marketing-automation] Prospects are scored, based on their activities, and receive targeted content and messaging, thus nurturing them from first interest through to sale.
[src:crm-systems/marketing-automation] (B2C) sales cycles, Marketing Automation involves multiple areas of marketing and is really the marriage of email marketing technology coupled with a structured sales process.
[src:crm-systems/marketing-automation] Has a focus on automating the process of advertising, usually focusing on the campaign lifecycle management.
[src:crm-systems/marketing-automation] — traditionally manually operated across different adtech platforms — that with advertising automation is automated.
[src:crm-systems/marketing-automation] This generates an automated creation of placement, automated pushing of trackers to the various media, and automatic management of the creation of UTM parameters.
[src:crm-systems/marketing-automation] While commonly used among big advertisers to simplify complex infrastructures and processes, advertising automation is paving the way to make advertising accessible to unskilled users.
[src:crm-systems/marketing-automation] Encompasses automation of internal marketing processes.
[src:crm-systems/marketing-automation] These include budgeting and planning, workflow and approvals, the marketing calendar, internal collaboration, digital asset creation, and management and essentially everything that supports the operational efficiency of the internal marketing function.
[src:crm-systems/marketing-automation] ) administrator to set up a complex series of rules to trigger action items for internal sales and marketing professionals to manually process (designing files, sending letters, sending email campaigns).
[src:crm-systems/marketing-automation] This type of system increases the marketer's ability to deliver relevant content to relevant individuals at relevant times.
[src:crm-systems/marketing-automation] Limitations may apply, based on the human resource capacity of an organization and their level of commitment to the tasks as they are assigned.
[src:crm-systems/marketing-automation] Advanced workflow automation's can be created to support the entire customer journey, including awareness, consideration, decision and long term loyalty.
[src:crm-systems/marketing-automation] As of 25 May 2018 the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) came into effect in the EU, this has had a large impact on the way marketing teams and organizations can manage their consumer data.
[src:crm-systems/marketing-automation] Any organization using marketing automation tracking is required to ask consent from the consumer as well as provide transparency on how the data will be processed.
[src:crm-systems/marketing-automation] Similarly, the California Consumer Privacy Act (CCPA), which took effect on January 1, 2020, introduced strict data privacy laws for residents of California.
[src:crm-systems/marketing-automation] The CCPA grants consumers the right to know what personal data is collected, the purpose of collection, and with whom it is shared, and to opt out of the sale of their personal information.
[src:crm-systems/marketing-automation] Consumers are directly impacted by marketing automation.
[src:crm-systems/marketing-automation] Consumers provide data for companies, and companies use algorithms to determine products and services to market towards the consumer.
[src:crm-systems/marketing-automation] The products and services are personalized based on the collected data for each individual.
[src:crm-systems/marketing-automation] The use of marketing automation is interpreted as an efficient customer experience while others interpret a loss of autonomy for the consumer.
[src:crm-systems/marketing-automation] Campaign and customer analysis help organizations create appropriate offers and gain insights from information collected during previous campaigns.
[src:crm-systems/marketing-automation] Campaign management oversees all customer communications across multiple channels, monitors customer responses, and reports on campaign performance and outcomes.
[src:crm-systems/marketing-automation] Data warehousing pulls customer information together from different systems and channels.
[src:crm-systems/marketing-automation] After a user visits a merchant's website and navigates away, an automated email can be triggered to be sent out to that user.
[src:crm-systems/marketing-automation] They can be reminded of an abandoned shopping cart, a subscription that is about to expire, or be welcomed if they are a new customer.
[src:crm-systems/marketing-automation] Coupons and messages can be tailored based on past purchases.
[src:crm-systems/marketing-automation] Software can also automate the creation of product landing pages and chatbots for customer support.
[src:crm-systems/marketing-automation] According to Gartner, the B2B automation market was valued at $2.1 billion in 2020 and more than $2.74 billion in 2021.
